The paper deals with algorithmic problems related to systems of linear equations and satisfiability, which are typically studied in computer science subfields such as data structures (cs.DS), computational complexity (cs.CC), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), computational geometry (cs.CG), and machine learning (cs.LG). The use of algebraic techniques and parameterized complexity also suggests a possible connection to algebraic algorithms (cs.SC) and theoretical computer science (cs.IT). However, the focus on specific problem instances and parameterized above-average formulations makes these categories less likely.
